export const notes = `
<h2>Diversity of Matter — Physical Properties</h2>
<p class="topic-desc">States of matter · Kinetic particle model · Changes of state · Heating &amp; cooling curves · Density · Diffusion · Brownian motion</p>

<div class="notes-card">
  <h3>1. Physical Properties</h3>
  <p>A <strong>physical property</strong> is one that can be measured or observed <em>without changing the chemical composition</em> of a substance.</p>
  <table>
    <tr><th>Property</th><th>Description</th><th>Example</th></tr>
    <tr><td>Density</td><td>Mass per unit volume (ρ = m/V)</td><td>Iron: 7.87 g/cm³</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Melting point</td><td>Temperature solid → liquid</td><td>Ice: 0 °C</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Boiling point</td><td>Temperature liquid → gas throughout</td><td>Water: 100 °C</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Solubility</td><td>Max mass of solute per 100 g solvent</td><td>NaCl: ~36 g per 100 g water</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Electrical conductivity</td><td>Ability to conduct electric current</td><td>Copper: good; wood: poor</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Thermal conductivity</td><td>Ability to conduct heat</td><td>Copper: good; plastic: poor</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Hardness</td><td>Resistance to scratching</td><td>Diamond: hardest; talc: softest</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Malleability</td><td>Can be hammered into sheets</td><td>Gold foil</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Ductility</td><td>Can be drawn into wires</td><td>Copper wire</td></tr>
  </table>
  <p>Physical properties differ from <strong>chemical properties</strong> (e.g., flammability, reactivity with acid) which involve a change in chemical identity.</p>
</div>

<div class="notes-card">
  <h3>2. States of Matter &amp; The Kinetic Particle Model</h3>
  <table>
    <tr><th>State</th><th>Particle Spacing</th><th>Arrangement</th><th>Movement</th><th>Forces</th></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>Solid</strong></td><td>Very close</td><td>Orderly lattice</td><td>Vibrate about fixed positions</td><td>Very strong</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>Liquid</strong></td><td>Close</td><td>Disordered</td><td>Slide over each other</td><td>Moderate</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>Gas</strong></td><td>Far apart</td><td>Random</td><td>Rapid random motion in all directions</td><td>Negligible</td></tr>
  </table>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Kinetic Particle Model</strong>: All matter is made of tiny particles in <em>constant random motion</em>. Temperature is related to the <em>average kinetic energy</em> of particles.</li>
    <li>Gases fill any container because particles have high kinetic energy and negligible attractive forces.</li>
    <li>Gases can be compressed easily — large empty spaces between particles.</li>
    <li>Liquids take the shape of their container but retain a fixed volume.</li>
    <li><strong>Gas pressure</strong>: Caused by particles constantly colliding with container walls. Higher temperature → faster particles → greater pressure.</li>
  </ul>
  <div class="example">
    <strong>Brownian Motion:</strong> Random zigzag movement of small particles (e.g., smoke, pollen) bombarded by invisible fluid molecules — direct evidence for the kinetic particle model.
  </div>
</div>

<div class="notes-card">
  <h3>3. Changes of State</h3>
  <table>
    <tr><th>Change</th><th>Process</th><th>Energy</th></tr>
    <tr><td>Melting</td><td>Solid → Liquid</td><td>Endothermic (absorbs heat)</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Freezing / Solidification</td><td>Liquid → Solid</td><td>Exothermic (releases heat)</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Evaporation / Boiling</td><td>Liquid → Gas</td><td>Endothermic (absorbs heat)</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Condensation</td><td>Gas → Liquid</td><td>Exothermic (releases heat)</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Sublimation</td><td>Solid → Gas (directly)</td><td>Endothermic</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Deposition</td><td>Gas → Solid (directly)</td><td>Exothermic</td></tr>
  </table>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Boiling vs Evaporation</strong>: Boiling occurs at a fixed temperature throughout the liquid (bubbles form). Evaporation occurs at the surface at any temperature below the boiling point.</li>
    <li><strong>Effect of impurities</strong>: Impurities <em>lower</em> the melting point and cause melting over a <em>range</em> of temperatures. Impurities <em>raise</em> the boiling point.</li>
    <li><strong>Effect of altitude</strong>: Lower atmospheric pressure → lower boiling point (e.g., ~90 °C at 3 000 m).</li>
    <li><strong>Sublimation examples</strong>: Dry ice (solid CO₂), iodine crystals, mothballs (naphthalene).</li>
  </ul>
</div>

<div class="notes-card">
  <h3>4. Heating &amp; Cooling Curves</h3>
  <p>For a <strong>pure substance</strong>, a heating curve has two flat (plateau) regions:</p>
  <div class="example">
    <strong>Heating curve shape:</strong><br>
    → Slope up (solid heating) → Flat plateau (melting at m.p.) → Slope up (liquid heating) → Flat plateau (boiling at b.p.) → Slope up (gas heating)
  </div>
  <ul>
    <li>The <strong>flat region</strong> = change of state; temperature is constant because heat energy is used to break intermolecular forces, not increase kinetic energy.</li>
    <li>A <strong>cooling curve</strong> is the reverse: slope down → plateau (solidifying) → slope down.</li>
    <li><strong>Pure substance</strong>: sharp, flat plateau at fixed temperature.</li>
    <li><strong>Impure substance</strong>: melts/freezes over a range, plateau is sloped or broad.</li>
  </ul>
</div>

<div class="notes-card">
  <h3>5. Density</h3>
  <div class="formula">
    ρ (density) = m (mass) ÷ V (volume)<br>
    SI unit: kg/m³ &nbsp;|&nbsp; Also common: g/cm³<br>
    Conversion: 1 g/cm³ = 1 000 kg/m³
  </div>
  <ul>
    <li>Density is an <strong>intensive property</strong> — does not depend on sample size.</li>
    <li><strong>Floating/Sinking</strong>: Object floats if its density &lt; fluid density; sinks if &gt; fluid density; remains suspended if equal.</li>
    <li>Typical densities: Water = 1.0 g/cm³; Ice = 0.92 g/cm³; Mercury = 13.6 g/cm³; Air ≈ 0.0012 g/cm³.</li>
    <li>Ice is less dense than liquid water — unusual property due to hydrogen bonding.</li>
    <li><strong>Steel ships float</strong>: Overall density of ship (steel hull + enclosed air) &lt; 1.0 g/cm³.</li>
  </ul>
  <div class="example">
    <strong>Example:</strong> Metal block: mass = 810 g, volume = 300 cm³<br>
    ρ = 810 ÷ 300 = <strong>2.7 g/cm³</strong>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="notes-card">
  <h3>6. Diffusion</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Diffusion</strong>: Net movement of particles from a region of <em>higher concentration</em> to <em>lower concentration</em> due to random particle motion.</li>
    <li>Diffusion is <em>faster</em> in gases than liquids (particles have more energy and space).</li>
    <li>Diffusion rate increases with <em>higher temperature</em> (more kinetic energy).</li>
    <li>Example: Perfume spreads across a room; purple dye spreads through water.</li>
    <li><strong>Brownian motion</strong> provides evidence that particles are in continuous random motion.</li>
  </ul>
  <div class="example">
    <strong>Brownian Motion Experiment:</strong> Smoke particles viewed under microscope show random, erratic (zigzag) movement — caused by invisible air molecules bombarding them from all sides.
  </div>
</div>

<div class="notes-card">
  <h3>7. Solubility &amp; Physical Properties of Metals</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Solubility</strong>: Maximum mass of solute that dissolves in 100 g of solvent at a specific temperature.</li>
    <li>Solubility generally increases with temperature for solids dissolving in water.</li>
    <li><strong>Metals</strong> have characteristic physical properties: high density, high melting/boiling points, good conductors of heat and electricity, malleable, ductile, shiny lustre.</li>
    <li><strong>Thermal conductivity</strong>: Metal spoon feels colder than wooden spoon at same temperature — metal conducts heat away from hand faster.</li>
  </ul>
</div>
`

